        I've been excited for this game ever since the Japanese release and I purposely avoided watching any gameplay footage so I could go in as blind as possible. It was well worth it because this game no doubt ended up living up to my expectations!
        Even though I love turn-based combat I wasn't sure if it would translate well to the Yakuza series because I had gotten so used to the beat em up style combat. Given that RGG Studio started fresh with a new protagonist and took the time to explain the 
        canonical reason for the new combat system it ended up fitting perfectly. They did an excellent job of preserving the spirit of past Yakuza games while still trying something new.
        The amount of things to do in Ijincho was excellent. Just like in all the past Yakuza games it had that feeling of finding something new to do around every corner of the city and it is significantly bigger than the places featured in past Yakuza games. My only complaint was 
        that there was a lack of side content in story mode.
        Despite the change in protagonists and combat this still a Yakuza game through and through. Just like previous entries it has a perfect balance of absolute ridiculousness in the sub stories/mini games and thrilling crime drama with emotional moments in the main story.

The amount of jobs was a little overwhelming but thankfully the game isn't too punishing when you decide to switch to a different one.
