        DMC isn't an rpg...but there is an upgrade system. It's quite simple tho, basically you have locked movesets and upgrades which you unlock by spending Red Orbs (currency). The game is quite generous with these; so don't worry about any grind. There is no "tree" tho, you basically unlock everything by the end of the game.

The game is linear, so you there's not minimap since it's very hard to get lost...but DMC5 did go thru the trouble of implementing a waypoint system that shows you where you gotta go.

The game isn't complicated, so that is a plus for you...it does have a lot of gameplay depth tho. It's hard to say if you'll like it since you haven't played any "stylish action" game before; but if it's worth anything DMC5 is probably the best game of the genre so far.

If you're on console, i suggest you trying out the demo to get a feel of how the game is like. No demo for PC sadly, tho you could buy it on Steam and get a refund if you don't like it (just make sure you don't go over that 2h limit)
The maps are also mostly linear, so you don't need to worry about navigation very much. The objective is to fight through the level and face the level boss.   
Even though DMC5 is the most forgiving in the serie, If you are not use to them the DMC Can be hard, though the easy difficulty should be accessible for everyone i think.
